Popularity of Programming Languages

The Dataset

How can we tell what programming languages are currently most widely used, as well as which languages seem to be growing in popularity or fading over time? One source of data is the programming question-and-answer site Stack Overflow. Each question has a tag or tags that describe its topic(s) and are searchable by users. For example, there is a tag for languages like R or Python, as well as for packages like ggplot2 or pandas. By analyzing data on the number of questions tagged for a language, we can get some sense of how many people might be using it. Individuals can access data about Stack Overflow from the Stack Exchange Data Explorer. The rows of the dataset contain frequency counts for individual question tags by year across several years (20082018), as well as the total count of all tags for the given year.

The Importance of Good Handwashing

The Datasets

Postpartum infections, known puerperal fever or childbed fever, are caused by bacteria invading the female reproductive tract following childbirth or miscarriage. Historically it has been a major cause of maternal mortality and it still impacts poorer regions. Hungarian physician Dr.Ignaz Semmelweis (18181965), a physician at Vienna General Hospital, pioneered antiseptic procedures to try to prevent such infections. He theorized that the cause was contaminated hands among doctors delivering the babies. The concept of germs were not known at the time, and so routine handwashing before procedures was uncommon. We will analyze Semmelweiss data to help confirm or refute his theory. One dataset has information about women giving birth in two different clinics at Vienna General Hospital for the years 1841 to 1846. It includes total number of births for the year, as well as the total maternal deaths. The second dataset contains similar data by month from before and after Semmelweis instituted an antiseptic handwashing protocol at Clinic 1 near the end of May 1847common sense now, but radical at the time! The mortality rate in each time interval is the number of maternal deaths per 100 births.

handwashing_start = as.Date("1847-06-01")

monthly_deaths <- read_csv("monthly_deaths.csv") %>% 
  mutate(mortality_rate = 100 * deaths / births,
         handwashing = ifelse(date < handwashing_start, "dirty", "washed"))

Identifying the Problem

Vienna General Hospital served a large volume of pregnant women in the early 1800s, so they added a second maternity clinic in 1833. By May 1841, the original Clinic 1 was served by doctors and medical students, while midwives and their students served at Clinic 2. Midwives only tended to birthing women, but medical students also spent time in the autopsy rooms examining cadavers. The germ theory of disease had not yet been developed, so no one thought to wash their hands when going from the morgue to the delivery room. Yikes! Semmelweis thought medical students were transferring some kind of morbid poison from dissected cadavers to the maternity patients.

Semmelweiss Intervention

Semmelweis introduced a handwashing protocol using chlorinated lime, which is now known to be a disinfectant. The descriptive analyses below compare maternal mortality rates in Clinic 1 before and after his protocol was introduced.

# A tibble: 2 x 6
  handwashing  xbar  stdv     n lower_fence upper_fence

2 washed       2.11  1.52    22       -2.17        6.22

Does Handwashing Reduce Mortality?

The goal of handwashing was to reduce maternal mortality. On average, were the rates of maternal mortality significantly lower after the handwashing protocol was introduced? The permutation test below seeks to answer that question. The 95% bootstrap percentile is also provided to estimate the difference in mean rates.

# CODE CHUNK #2

teststat <- summaries$xbar[1] - summaries$xbar[2]     

testdata <- monthly_deaths %>% pull(mortality_rate)   
total_n  <- length(testdata)                          
group_n  <- summaries$n[1]                            

sims     <- 10^5-1
randstat <- numeric(sims)

for (i in 1:sims) {
  index       <- sample(total_n, group_n)
  randstat[i] <- mean(testdata[index]) - mean(testdata[-index])
}

# CODE CHUNK #3

data_dirty <- monthly_deaths %>% filter(handwashing == "dirty") %>% pull(mortality_rate)
n_dirty    <- length(data_dirty)

data_clean <- monthly_deaths %>% filter(handwashing == "washed") %>% pull(mortality_rate)
n_clean    <- length(data_clean)

sims       <- 10^5
mean_diffs <- numeric(sims)

for (i in 1:sims) {
    sample_dirty <- sample(data_dirty, n_dirty, replace = TRUE)
    sample_clean <- sample(data_clean, n_clean, replace = TRUE)  
    mean_diffs[i] <- mean(sample_dirty) - mean(sample_clean)
}
